			<title><![CDATA[The Vita is the best console you aren't playing - Part 2]]></title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76774-The-Vita-is-the-best-console-you-aren-t-playing-Part-2&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Wed, 07 May 2014 05:40:28 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[I've been meaning to post updated impressions on the Vita for a few months now but always end up forgetting. Sony is launching a new model of this with a longer battery life (by dropping the OLED) so figured now was a good time to bump the thread. 
 
Edit: I remembered bumping old threads causes...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I've been meaning to post updated impressions on the Vita for a few months now but always end up forgetting. Sony is launching a new model of this with a longer battery life (by dropping the OLED) so figured now was a good time to bump the thread.<br />
<br />
Edit: I remembered bumping old threads causes Nadiar headaches. I wasn't sure how old a thread had to be to cause problems so went ahead and made a new one. You can find the original: <a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76274-The-Vita-the-best-console-you-aren-t-playing-and-why-you-should" target="_blank">here</a><br />
<br />
<br />
So, I love Nintendo handhelds. I love Nintendo games. But I think I like my Vita more than my 3DS. The interface is great. Downloading things from PSN is incredibly easy. PS+ itself is fantastic. I haven't even gotten around to playing the &quot;big&quot; titles like Soul Sacrifice yet, I've just been playing the lower tier titles in idle moments. It's just extremely convenient with how many games you can fit on one of the decently sized memory cards. I've sadly just about filled up mine though.<br />
<br />
The 3DS does do a few things better. Ignoring how you feel about Nintendo's games, the games themselves are easier to swap in and out. The power cable is smaller and connects to the top so it's easier to play while charging. The battery life is a little better (I think).<br />
<br />
The battery life on the 3DS never bothered me, but I did have to cut a Guacamelee session on my Vita short because of it. I ended up buying a portable charging battery as a result. It's pretty great. The only downside is that it charges kind of slowly, but if you absolutely can't wait you can play with it plugged in, assuming you can put up with it being plugged in on the bottom. The headphone jack is also on the bottom, not a huge deal, but I find it to be kind of annoying.<br />
<br />
I never did get a special grip for the thing, since I wanted it to easily fit into my carrying case. I did eventually get used to the feel of it in my hands. My one remaining complaint is with the select and start buttons. They are sort of in a weird spot and are kind of hard to press. You can't accidentally pause this way, but it takes kind of a silly amount of effort to do so intentionally as a result.<br />
<br />
<br />
So I mentioned Guacamelee. I agree it's a fantastic game. Think I had a little bit of trouble with the controls though. That game's more advanced techniques require quite a bit of complicated contortions with your fingers. On a gamepad I think I would have been okay, but the buttons were kind of cramped for some of that crap.<br />
<br />
I also played Killzone Mercenary, which was also (surprisingly) fantastic. I ended up liking it far more than the PS3 games. Instead of being completely scripted, you were given the opportunity to choose your own loadouts for each mission (as well as being able to change them mid mission). The story is that you are a mercenary so you are fighting for money. The money you earn is how you pay for equipment, which varies between different kinds of guns and grenades, to body armor and trinkets. The trinkets are very expensive but also very cool. You can have a personal shield, a drone that scans enemies and lets you see through walls, a shoulder mounted rocket launcher, etc. They are really expensive though, so you won't get everything in one playthrough.<br />
<br />
Luckily the levels are designed with multiple playthroughs in mind. They had a little bit of variety and weren't just corridors, you had the option of stealth, etc etc. I don't know if this game was contracted out to another developer or what, but it would have been a great shooter on any system, let alone a handheld one.<br />
<br />
Haven't really played much else of note on it, just short sessions in some of the PS+ freebies. Sonic Racing is pretty good. The Urban Trials stunt bike game was okay. Stuff like that. Every month in PS+ gets you two more Vita freebies. It's a pretty easy way of always having something to play on it, and since Vita titles tend to be smaller than PS3 titles, it's a pretty convenient device to use with digital games. If it weren't for the memory card situation I would treat it like a PC and go full digital without ever looking back.<br />
<br />
P.S. I never mentioned it before, but I'm glad you liked Persona 4: Golden Maledict. I know we go back and forth about jrpgs sometimes, but Persona 4 was probably my favorite in years. I'm not sure if there was anything for the PS3 that even came close. I'm looking forward to experience it again with Golden.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
