			<title>Final Fantasy VII</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76749-Final-Fantasy-VII&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Wed, 30 Apr 2014 14:19:22 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Playing through this again after more than a decade.  Might have some more comprehensive thoughts at some point but for now: 
 
Story-wise, it's still pretty good.  Not great, but good enough to keep me engaged for several hours on a plane ride.  The decision to start the game in Midgar and spend...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Playing through this again after more than a decade.  Might have some more comprehensive thoughts at some point but for now:<br />
<br />
Story-wise, it's still pretty good.  Not great, but good enough to keep me engaged for several hours on a plane ride.  The decision to start the game in Midgar and spend most of the first 5-10 hours of the game in restricted set of dingy, dismal areas (slums, reactors, sewers, and piles of rubble) or the complete opposite (Shinra headquarters) was an interesting decision, given that it puts off one of the core gameplay features (world map exploration) for so long.  While I question it from a game design perspective, I must admit it was a pretty good way to start off the story.  <br />
<br />
The game's introduction is superb.  It's perhaps one of the best in the series.  No lengthy expository segment, no gratuitous visuals.  After two minutes, they've foreshadowed Aeris and the Lifestream, established the setting of Midgar, introduced Avalanche, and introduced Cloud.  You take control of him immediately (after a the terse &quot;C'mon newcomer, follow me!&quot; from Barret), with full access to the party menu, then are in combat moments later.  The first mission ends with a large explosion.<br />
<br />
Really, it doesn't get better than that.  Contrast with, say, Final Fantasy XII...<br />
<br />
But ugh, the minigames.  Most of them are downright awful.  I hate them and hate every gamer who likes them.  Except for the motorcycle segment (which was tolerable), the chocobo racing (which was just boring) and the snowboarding (which I think I liked), I don't remember ANY of them.  They are not remotely memorable, they are nothing but annoying.<br />
<br />
There's also a lot of minor but tedious delays everywhere.  Part of this was playstation limitations I think, but battle introductions are 8-9 seconds as opposed to 2 seconds on the SNES.  (For reference, FFIX's battle intro sequences are a whopping 15 seconds).  Menus take a long time to open.  Zone transitions take a long time.  The summon spells are famous for being long.  It all adds up.  And then, while the pre-rendered 2D backgrounds are gorgeous, they're much harder to navigate than the old grid-based JRPG format.  It's much smoother than it could be, but still gets annoying at times.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
